What is a Skill in Antigravity?

A Skill is a reusable capability that an AI agent can load only when needed.

Think of it like an app on your phone.

You don't keep the Calculator app open all the time.
You open it only when you need to calculate something.

Similarly, Antigravity loads a Skill only when the user's request requires it.

Simple Definition

A Skill is:

A folder
Contains a file called SKILL.md
May also contain:
Python scripts
Bash scripts
Templates
Reference files

Example:

weather-skill/
│
├── SKILL.md
├── weather.py
├── cities.json
└── template.md
What is SKILL.md?

This is the instruction file.

It tells the AI:

When to use the skill
What the skill does
Which scripts to execute
Expected output

Example:

Name: Weather Skill

Purpose:
Get current weather.

Use when:
User asks about weather.

Steps:
1. Call weather.py
2. Format output

Think of SKILL.md as the instruction manual for the skill.

Why not put everything in the System Prompt?
System Prompt

Loaded every time.

Start AI
     ↓
Load everything

Even if the user asks:

"Tell me a joke."

the AI still loads weather instructions, Git instructions, database instructions, etc.

This wastes context.

Skills

Loaded only when needed.

Example:

User:

"Generate database migration."

AI loads:

Database Skill

User:

"Summarize this PDF."

AI loads:

PDF Skill

Much more efficient.

Real-Life Analogy

Imagine a hospital.

Doctors don't carry every medical book all day.

Instead:

Patient:

"Heart pain"

Doctor opens:

❤️ Cardiology book

Patient:

"Skin allergy"

Doctor opens:

🩺 Dermatology book

Same doctor.

Different knowledge loaded.

Skills work exactly like this.

What does "On-Demand" mean?

Suppose your project has:

30 Skills

Examples:

Docker Skill
Git Skill
Database Skill
React Skill
Python Skill
AWS Skill
Firebase Skill

If all 30 loaded every time:

❌ Huge context

❌ Slower reasoning

❌ Higher token usage

Instead:

User:

"Deploy my app."

AI loads only:

Docker Skill
AWS Skill
Git Skill

Everything else stays unloaded.

Capability Extension

Skills don't only explain things.

They can perform actions.

Example:

User:

"Generate changelog."

Instead of writing one manually,

AI executes:

git log

Collects commits.

Creates:

Version 2.0

Added login

Fixed bug

Improved UI

The Skill performed real work.

Example 1

User:

"Create a Python virtual environment."

Skill executes:

python -m venv venv

No manual typing.

Example 2

User:

"Convert all PNG images to JPG."

Skill executes Python:

convert_images.py

Automatically.

